# Pensees — Project Soul

Authoritative, always-applied guidance for every agent and contributor working in
this repository. Compiled by DevolaFlow into `AGENTS.md` and the
`.cursor/rules/` bundle; do not hand-edit those outputs.

## 1. Project North Star

Pensees is at the **greenfield stage**. The repository currently contains only
governance scaffolding and this soul layer — no product code, no architecture
commitments, no chosen language or framework. Treat every contribution as a
deliberate first brick: prefer reversible, well-explained moves over speculative
breadth. This soul will be refined as the product takes shape; when product
identity, domain model, or stack choices crystallize, propose updates to this
file (and the compiler will propagate them) rather than smuggling implicit
assumptions into code.

## 2. Engineering Principles

These principles distill the workspace-level governance rules that already apply
to this repo. They are durable and apply across whatever stack Pensees adopts.

- **Protected branches are sacred.** Never push directly to `main`, `master`,
  `yc_dev`, or `production`. Always branch off, then open a Merge Request / Pull
  Request for review.
- **No silent failures.** Never swallow an error with a bare `try`/`except` (or
  language equivalent). Either log it, re-throw it, or return an explicit error
  state. The only exception is when the operator has explicitly asked for
  "best-effort" execution on a non-critical task, and that exception must be
  called out in the diff.
- **Braces always (C++).** In C++ code, every `if` / `else if` / `else` body
  must be wrapped in braces. No single-line unbracketed bodies, even for
  one-liners. Apply the same "no implicit blocks" instinct to any language with
  ambiguous control-flow syntax.
- **Documentation Protocol.** If a `doc_auto/` directory exists, read it before
  changing related code, and update it (with a timestamp on the change) when
  your work invalidates it.
- **Lark CLI footer.** When using `lark-cli` for any write/send operation other
  than mail, append the standard provenance footer
  (`本X由飞书工具 Lark-Cli X`) so downstream readers know the artifact was
  produced by an agent tool.
- **Mandatory verification.** New logic gets tests (unit and/or integration) in
  the same change. Never mark a verification step as "todo" to unblock a merge,
  and never disable an existing test without an in-MR justification.

## 3. Quality Bar

- **Tests are part of the change, not a follow-up.** A change without a test
  story is incomplete. If the surface is genuinely untestable, document why in
  the MR description.
- **Errors must be observable.** Logged with context, surfaced to callers, or
  promoted to an explicit error type. Silent fallbacks are a defect.
- **No direct pushes to protected branches.** Every change lands via MR/PR
  with at least one reviewer signal (human or designated bot) before merge.
- **Reproducibility over cleverness.** Prefer code, config, and tooling that
  produce the same result on a teammate's machine and in CI as on yours.
- **Boring is good at greenfield.** Until Pensees has a real product shape,
  favor the most boring, most reversible option. Avoid load-bearing
  abstractions before the second concrete use case.

## 4. Collaboration Conventions

- **Branch naming.** Use a short, prefixed slug:
  `feat/<scope>-<summary>`, `fix/<scope>-<summary>`, `chore/<scope>-<summary>`,
  `docs/<scope>-<summary>`, `refactor/<scope>-<summary>`. Keep slugs lowercase,
  hyphen-separated, and under ~50 chars.
- **Commit messages.** Use Conventional Commits
  (`type(scope): summary`, e.g. `feat(rules): add soul layer`). Keep the
  subject under 72 chars; explain the "why" in the body when non-obvious.
  Reference task IDs (e.g. `W1.T1.author-soul-recompile`) when they exist.
- **Pull / Merge Requests.** One logical change per MR. Description states the
  intent, the user-visible effect, and the test evidence. Request review from
  at least one human or designated reviewer; do not self-approve protected
  changes.
- **Generated artifacts.** Files marked as auto-generated
  (e.g. `AGENTS.md`, `.cursor/rules/repo-governance.mdc`,
  `.rules/.compile-hashes.json`) must be regenerated through their compiler,
  never hand-edited. Edit the source `.rules/*.mdc` layers and re-run
  `devola-init local`.

## 5. When in Doubt

If the next action is destructive, expands scope beyond what the operator asked
for, touches files outside the task's declared ownership, or trades a workspace
rule for short-term convenience: **pause and ask the operator first**. A short
clarifying exchange is always cheaper than an unwind. Concrete triggers:

- About to delete, rename, or rewrite history of anything you did not just
  create in this session.
- About to push to, or force-push, a protected branch.
- About to suppress an error, skip a test, or disable a check to make CI pass.
- About to introduce a new language, framework, service, or external dependency
  while Pensees still has no settled stack.
- About to modify files outside the task's `Owned files` list — even "just to
  fix a small thing".

When the answer is unclear, default to the smaller, more reversible move and
surface the question in your status report instead of guessing.
